|last2=Yamada|first2=Y.|year= 1991|chapter=Ogawa's Siraya/Makatao/Taivoan comparative vocabulary|editor1=S. Tsuchida|editor2=Y. Yamada|editor3=T. Moriguchi|title=Linguistic Materials of the Formosan Sinicized Populations I: Siraya and Basai|publisher=The University of Tokyo, Linguistics Department|place=Tokyo}}\n*{{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Wilson|first=Richard W|title=Learning To Be Chinese: The Political Socialization of Children in Taiwan|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology Press|place=Cambridge, MA|year=1970}} {{ISBN|0-262-23041-0}}.\n*{{wikicite|id=Yeh-2003|reference= Yeh, Yu-ting (2003). Atayal Narratives and Folktales, in the [http://formosan.sinica.edu.tw/en/archive_contents.htm Formosan Language Archive]. Taipei: The Institute of Linguistics, Academia Sinica}} Accessed 13 April 2007.\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv|last=Zeitoun|first=Elizabeth|last2=Yu|first2=Ching-Hua |url=http://aclclp.org.tw/clclp/v10n2/v10n2a2.pdf |title= The Formosan Language Archive: Linguistic Analysis and Language Processing |journal=Computational Linguistics and Chinese Language Processing|volume=10|issue=2|pages= 167\u2013200|year=2005}}\n*{{cite book |year=2014 |title=The Republic of China Yearbook 2014 |publisher=Executive Yuan, R.O.C. |url = http://www.ey.gov.tw/Upload/UserFiles/YB%202014%20all%20100dpi.pdf |accessdate=2015-02-25 |isbn=9789860423020 |ref = {{harvid|Exec. Yuan|2014}} }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Prone to spam|date=March 2016}}\n{{Z148}}\n{{Commons and category|Taiwanese aborigines|Taiwanese aborigines}}{{Library resources box}}\n\n*Andrade, Tonio (2002). ''[http://www.gutenberg-e.org/andrade/index.html How Taiwan Became Chinese: Dutch, Spanish, and Han Colonization in the Seventeenth Century]''. Columbia University Press, Gutenberg e-Books.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090106140149/http://www.tacp.gov.tw/tacpeng/ ''Taiwan Aboriginal Culture Park,''] Bureau of Cultural Parks, [[Council of Indigenous Peoples]], [[Executive Yuan]].\n*[http://www.apc.gov.tw/portal/index.html?lang=en_US Council of Indigenous Peoples (Taiwan)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170603060416/http://www.dmtip.gov.tw/Eng/Index.htm Digital Museum of Taiwan Indigenous Peoples]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100629224254/http://formosan.sinica.edu.tw/en/intro.htm Academia Sinica: Formosan Language Archive]\n*[http://weber.ucsd.edu/~dkjordan/chin/hbtaiwantribes.html An overview of the people groups]\n*[http://www.taiwanfirstnations.org/ Taiwan First Nations]\n*[http://academic.reed.edu/formosa/formosa_index_page/formosa_index.html Reed Institute's Formosa Digital Library]\n*[http://www.museum.org.tw/SYMM_en/index.htm Shung Ye Museum of Formosan Aborigines official site]\n*[http://www.sinica.edu.tw/tit/museums/1294_shung-ye.html Shung Ye Museum of Formosan Aborigines another description]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4649257.stm BBC News: Taiwan's aborigines find new voice]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20181120202019/http://www.titv.org.tw/ Taiwan Indigenous Television]\n\n{{-}}\n\n{{Taiwanese aborigines}}\n{{Taiwanese aboriginal areas}}\n{{Taiwan related articles}}\n{{Indigenous peoples by continent}}\n{{East Asian topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taiwanese Aborigines}}\n\n[[Category:Taiwanese indigenous peoples| ]]\n[[Category:Ancient peoples of Asia]]\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples of East Asia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Headhunting]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese culture]]\n[[Category:Austronesian culture]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "Script-assisted fixes: perCS1andMOS:ITALICS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taiwanese_indigenous_peoples"}
{"title_page": "Eugene Scalia", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Eugene Scalia\n| image = Eugene Scalia.jpg\n| office = 28th [[United States Secretary of Labor]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| deputy = [[Patrick Pizzella]]\n| term_start = September 30, 2019\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = [[Alexander Acosta]]\n| successor =\n| office1 = [[United States Solicitor of Labor]]\n| president1 = [[George W. Bush]]\n| term_start1 = January 11, 2002\n| term_end1 = January 17, 2003\n| predecessor1 = Henry Solano\n| successor1 = [[Howard M. Radzely]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|8|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Cleveland|Cleveland, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse = Patricia\n| children = 7\n| father = [[Antonin Scalia]]\n| education = [[University of Virginia]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[University of Chicago]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''Eugene Scalia''' (born August 14, 1963)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lawcells.com/lawyer_167564_Eugene-Scalia.htm |title=Eugene Scalia |website=lawcells.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219020233/http://www.lawcells.com/lawyer_167564_Eugene-Scalia.htm |archivedate=February 19, 2014 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> is an American attorney who has served as the 28th [[United States Secretary of Labor]] since September 30, 2019. He was formerly a partner in the [[Washington, D.C.]] office of the [[law firm]] [[Gibson, Dunn & Crutcher]]; and previously served one year in the Department of Labor during the [[George W. Bush]] administration. He is a son of the late [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] Associate Justice [[Antonin Scalia]].\n\nIn July 2019, President [[Donald Trump]] nominated him to become the next secretary of labor,<ref name=\"DoL List\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/sol/mission/pastsolicitors.htm|title=Office of the Solicitor (SOL) - SOL History|website=www.dol.gov|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> and he was confirmed by the [[United States Senate|Senate]] on September 26.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/463250-senate-confirms-trump-labor-pick-scalia|title=Senate confirms Scalia as Labor secretary|last=Gangitano|first=Alex|date=2019-09-26|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> Scalia was sworn in on September 30, 2019.\n\n==Early life and education==\nScalia was born on August 14, 1963, in [[Cleveland|Cleveland, Ohio]], the son of [[Antonin Scalia]] and Maureen (McCarthy) Scalia. He attended the [[University of Virginia]] where he graduated with distinction with a major in economics, along with a minor in political science. He then attended the [[University of Chicago Law School]], where he was editor-in-chief of the ''[[University of Chicago Law Review]]'' and graduated ''[[cum laude]]'' with a [[Juris Doctor]] degree.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dol.gov/sol/info_about_sol/solicit5.htm|title=Information About the Solicitor of Labor|website=U.S. Department of Labor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020612211837/http://www.dol.gov/sol/info_about_sol/solicit5.htm|archive-date=2002-06-12|url-status=|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Swearing-in Ceremony for Labor Secretary Eugene Scalia (48823114616).jpg|thumb|left|Scalia being sworn in as [[United States Secretary of Labor|Secretary of Labor]] in 2019]]\n\nDuring 1985\u20131987 he was an aide to Education Secretary [[William Bennett|William J. Bennett]]. During 1992\u20131993 he served as Special Assistant to Attorney General [[William Barr|William P. Barr]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Scalia was in private practice in Washington, D.C. and Los Angeles, California.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2000, his firm Gibson, Dunn & Crutcher represented George W. Bush before the U.S. Supreme Court in ''[[Bush v. Gore]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zuckman|first=Jill|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-11-29/news/0011290353_1_james-rehnquist-chief-justice-william-rehnquist-recusal|title=Justice Scalia's Son A Lawyer In Firm Representing Bush Before Top Court|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=November 29, 2000|accessdate=November 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe served as the [[United States Solicitor of Labor|Solicitor of Labor]], having been appointed by President Bush in April 2001 and taken the position in January 2002 following a [[recess appointment]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Marquis|first=Christopher|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/12/us/bush-bypasses-senate-on-2-more-nominees.html|title=Bush Bypasses Senate on 2 More Nominees|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 12, 2002|accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> At the time, he was accused by Democratic Senators and labor groups of being hostile to workers and criticized for his articles criticizing [[ergonomics]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Clymer|first=Adam|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/03/us/parties-struggle-in-senate-over-labor-dept-nominee.html|title=Parties Struggle in Senate Over Labor Dept. Nominee|work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 3, 2001|accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/eugene-scalia-has-defended-wall-street-walmart-and-seaworld-now-hes-trumps-pick-for-labor-secretary/2019/07/19/6f2819f0-aa55-11e9-a3a6-ab670962db05_story.html|title=Eugene Scalia has defended Wall Street, Walmart and SeaWorld. Now he's Trump's pick for labor secretary.|last=|first=|date=2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> But a group of former career officials within the Department of Labor have since described Scalia as having been \"very supportive of enforcement litigation to vindicate the rights of workers, both at the trial and appellate levels\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=62fc98f0-e177-11e9-b42d-51c0899dd019&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxOS0wOS0wMy9zY2FsaWEtaGFzLWV4LW9mZmljaWFscy1zdXBwb3J0LWFzLXRydW1wLXMtbGFib3Itc2VjcmV0YXJ5LXBpY2s=|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> In 2019, ''The New York Times'' wrote that Scalia \"is perhaps best known for his opposition to a regulation that would have mandated greater protections for workers at risk of repetitive stress injuries\".<ref name=\":2\" /> The regulation was repealed by Congress in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osha.gov/archive/ergonomics-standard/archive.html|title=OSHA Ergonomics Background Page|website=www.osha.gov}}</ref>\n\nDuring his career in private practice, Scalia has a long record of defending major corporations against financial and labor regulations.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/business/economy/eugene-scalia-labor-lawsuits.html|title=Trump's Labor Pick Has Defended Corporations, and One Killer Whale|last=Scheiber|first=Noam|date=2019-07-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-22|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/labor-secretary-pick-eugene-scalia-has-strong-antiregulation-record-11563555638|title=Labor Secretary Pick Eugene Scalia Has Long Fought Rules Aimed at Business|last=Ackerman |first=David Harrison and Andrew|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/f1190939717c4858ad593e798989bc5a|title=Labor nominee Scalia has long record of opposing regulations|last=Sherman|first=Mark|last2=Freking|first2=Kevin|date=2019-07-19|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-07-22|last3=Colvin|first3=Jill}}</ref> Since 2003, he has defended Wall Street firms against financial oversight.<ref name=\":1\" /> A 2012 ''Bloomberg News'' article that profiled Scalia was headlined, \"Suing the Government? Call Scalia!\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nScalia argued for the plaintiffs in ''Wal-Mart v. Maryland'' in July 2006, which invalidated a state law under which large companies with at least 10,000 employees would have been required to spend at least 8% of their payroll on employee healthcare.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/07/19/AR2006071901145.html |title='Wal-Mart Law' in Md. Rejected By Court|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=July 20, 2006|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 18, 2019, President Trump announced he would nominate Scalia to be the next Secretary of Labor.<ref name=\"WSJ07182019\">{{cite news |last1=Lucey |first1=Catherine |last2=Andrews |first2=Natalie |title=Trump to Nominate Eugene Scalia to Serve as Labor Secretary |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-to-nominate-eugene-scalia-to-serve-as-labor-secretary-11563495481?mod=djemalertNEWS |accessdate=July 18, 2019 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |date=July 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1152010854176452608 |user=realDonaldTrump |title=I am pleased to announce that it is my intention to nominate Gene Scalia as the new Secretary of Labor. Gene has led a life of great success in the legal and labor field and is highly respected not only as a lawyer, but as a lawyer with great experience.{{nbsp}}... |date=July 18, 2019}}</ref> On September 26, 2019, the Senate confirmed his nomination by a vote of 53\u201344.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=116&session=1&vote=00313|title=U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 116th Congress - 1st Session|date=September 26, 2019|website=U.S. Senate|publisher=[[Government Publishing Office]]|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> Scalia was sworn in by Vice President [[Mike Pence]] on September 30.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.bloomberglaw.com/daily-labor-report/eugene-scalia-sworn-in-as-28th-labor-secretary|title=Eugene Scalia Sworn In as 28th Labor Secretary|website=news.bloomberglaw.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cspan/status/1178743232387260417|title=Eugene Scalia is sworn in as Secretary of Labor (@USDOL)pic.twitter.com/aQbvTmBYGP|date=September 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAs of 2019, Scalia and his wife Patricia have seven children, as As secretary of labor duringthe COVID-19 breakout, he decides to not pay Uber and Lyft drivers.  He should be impeached and as a catholic should be denied communion. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/osec|title=Office of the Secretary &#124; U.S. Department of Labor|website=www.dol.gov}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Eugene Scalia}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081024104947/http://gibsondunn.com/lawyers/escalia Official law firm biography]\n* {{C-SPAN|eugenescalia}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alexander Acosta]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of Labor]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{USSecLabor}}\n{{Current U.S. Cabinet}}\n{{Trump cabinet}}\n{{US Presidential Line of Succession}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scalia, Eugene}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lawyers who have represented the United States government]]\n[[Category:Trump administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Labor officials]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of Labor]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n[[Category:Washington, D.C. Republicans]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Eugene Scalia\n| image = Eugene Scalia.jpg\n| office = 28th [[United States Secretary of Labor]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| deputy = [[Patrick Pizzella]]\n| term_start = September 30, 2019\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = [[Alexander Acosta]]\n| successor =\n| office1 = [[United States Solicitor of Labor]]\n| president1 = [[George W. Bush]]\n| term_start1 = January 11, 2002\n| term_end1 = January 17, 2003\n| predecessor1 = Henry Solano\n| successor1 = [[Howard M. Radzely]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|8|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Cleveland|Cleveland, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse = Patricia\n| children = 7\n| father = [[Antonin Scalia]]\n| education = [[University of Virginia]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[University of Chicago]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''Eugene Scalia''' (born August 14, 1963)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lawcells.com/lawyer_167564_Eugene-Scalia.htm |title=Eugene Scalia |website=lawcells.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219020233/http://www.lawcells.com/lawyer_167564_Eugene-Scalia.htm |archivedate=February 19, 2014 |url-status=dead |accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> is an American attorney who has served as the 28th [[United States Secretary of Labor]] since September 30, 2019. He was formerly a partner in the [[Washington, D.C.]] office of the [[law firm]] [[Gibson, Dunn & Crutcher]]; and previously served one year in the Department of Labor during the [[George W. Bush]] administration. He is a son of the late [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] Associate Justice [[Antonin Scalia]].\n\nIn July 2019, President [[Donald Trump]] nominated him to become the next secretary of labor,<ref name=\"DoL List\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/sol/mission/pastsolicitors.htm|title=Office of the Solicitor (SOL) - SOL History|website=www.dol.gov|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> and he was confirmed by the [[United States Senate|Senate]] on September 26.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/463250-senate-confirms-trump-labor-pick-scalia|title=Senate confirms Scalia as Labor secretary|last=Gangitano|first=Alex|date=2019-09-26|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> Scalia was sworn in on September 30, 2019.\n\n==Early life and education==\nScalia was born on August 14, 1963, in [[Cleveland|Cleveland, Ohio]], the son of [[Antonin Scalia]] and Maureen (McCarthy) Scalia. He attended the [[University of Virginia]] where he graduated with distinction with a major in economics, along with a minor in political science. He then attended the [[University of Chicago Law School]], where he was editor-in-chief of the ''[[University of Chicago Law Review]]'' and graduated ''[[cum laude]]'' with a [[Juris Doctor]] degree.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dol.gov/sol/info_about_sol/solicit5.htm|title=Information About the Solicitor of Labor|website=U.S. Department of Labor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020612211837/http://www.dol.gov/sol/info_about_sol/solicit5.htm|archive-date=2002-06-12|url-status=|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Swearing-in Ceremony for Labor Secretary Eugene Scalia (48823114616).jpg|thumb|left|Scalia being sworn in as [[United States Secretary of Labor|Secretary of Labor]] in 2019]]\n\nDuring 1985\u20131987 he was an aide to Education Secretary [[William Bennett|William J. Bennett]]. During 1992\u20131993 he served as Special Assistant to Attorney General [[William Barr|William P. Barr]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Scalia was in private practice in Washington, D.C. and Los Angeles, California.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2000, his firm Gibson, Dunn & Crutcher represented George W. Bush before the U.S. Supreme Court in ''[[Bush v. Gore]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zuckman|first=Jill|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-11-29/news/0011290353_1_james-rehnquist-chief-justice-william-rehnquist-recusal|title=Justice Scalia's Son A Lawyer In Firm Representing Bush Before Top Court|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=November 29, 2000|accessdate=November 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe served as the [[United States Solicitor of Labor|Solicitor of Labor]], having been appointed by President Bush in April 2001 and taken the position in January 2002 following a [[recess appointment]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Marquis|first=Christopher|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/12/us/bush-bypasses-senate-on-2-more-nominees.html|title=Bush Bypasses Senate on 2 More Nominees|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 12, 2002|accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> At the time, he was accused by Democratic Senators and labor groups of being hostile to workers and criticized for his articles criticizing [[ergonomics]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Clymer|first=Adam|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/03/us/parties-struggle-in-senate-over-labor-dept-nominee.html|title=Parties Struggle in Senate Over Labor Dept. Nominee|work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 3, 2001|accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/eugene-scalia-has-defended-wall-street-walmart-and-seaworld-now-hes-trumps-pick-for-labor-secretary/2019/07/19/6f2819f0-aa55-11e9-a3a6-ab670962db05_story.html|title=Eugene Scalia has defended Wall Street, Walmart and SeaWorld. Now he's Trump's pick for labor secretary.|last=|first=|date=2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> But a group of former career officials within the Department of Labor have since described Scalia as having been \"very supportive of enforcement litigation to vindicate the rights of workers, both at the trial and appellate levels\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=62fc98f0-e177-11e9-b42d-51c0899dd019&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxOS0wOS0wMy9zY2FsaWEtaGFzLWV4LW9mZmljaWFscy1zdXBwb3J0LWFzLXRydW1wLXMtbGFib3Itc2VjcmV0YXJ5LXBpY2s=|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> In 2019, ''The New York Times'' wrote that Scalia \"is perhaps best known for his opposition to a regulation that would have mandated greater protections for workers at risk of repetitive stress injuries\".<ref name=\":2\" /> The regulation was repealed by Congress in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osha.gov/archive/ergonomics-standard/archive.html|title=OSHA Ergonomics Background Page|website=www.osha.gov}}</ref>\n\nDuring his career in private practice, Scalia has a long record of defending major corporations against financial and labor regulations.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/business/economy/eugene-scalia-labor-lawsuits.html|title=Trump's Labor Pick Has Defended Corporations, and One Killer Whale|last=Scheiber|first=Noam|date=2019-07-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-22|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/labor-secretary-pick-eugene-scalia-has-strong-antiregulation-record-11563555638|title=Labor Secretary Pick Eugene Scalia Has Long Fought Rules Aimed at Business|last=Ackerman |first=David Harrison and Andrew|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/f1190939717c4858ad593e798989bc5a|title=Labor nominee Scalia has long record of opposing regulations|last=Sherman|first=Mark|last2=Freking|first2=Kevin|date=2019-07-19|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-07-22|last3=Colvin|first3=Jill}}</ref> Since 2003, he has defended Wall Street firms against financial oversight.<ref name=\":1\" /> A 2012 ''Bloomberg News'' article that profiled Scalia was headlined, \"Suing the Government? Call Scalia!\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nScalia argued for the plaintiffs in ''Wal-Mart v. Maryland'' in July 2006, which invalidated a state law under which large companies with at least 10,000 employees would have been required to spend at least 8% of their payroll on employee healthcare.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/07/19/AR2006071901145.html |title='Wal-Mart Law' in Md. Rejected By Court|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=July 20, 2006|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 18, 2019, President Trump announced he would nominate Scalia to be the next Secretary of Labor.<ref name=\"WSJ07182019\">{{cite news |last1=Lucey |first1=Catherine |last2=Andrews |first2=Natalie |title=Trump to Nominate Eugene Scalia to Serve as Labor Secretary |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-to-nominate-eugene-scalia-to-serve-as-labor-secretary-11563495481?mod=djemalertNEWS |accessdate=July 18, 2019 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |date=July 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1152010854176452608 |user=realDonaldTrump |title=I am pleased to announce that it is my intention to nominate Gene Scalia as the new Secretary of Labor. Gene has led a life of great success in the legal and labor field and is highly respected not only as a lawyer, but as a lawyer with great experience.{{nbsp}}... |date=July 18, 2019}}</ref> On September 26, 2019, the Senate confirmed his nomination by a vote of 53\u201344.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=116&session=1&vote=00313|title=U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 116th Congress - 1st Session|date=September 26, 2019|website=U.S. Senate|publisher=[[Government Publishing Office]]|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> Scalia was sworn in by Vice President [[Mike Pence]] on September 30.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.bloomberglaw.com/daily-labor-report/eugene-scalia-sworn-in-as-28th-labor-secretary|title=Eugene Scalia Sworn In as 28th Labor Secretary|website=news.bloomberglaw.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cspan/status/1178743232387260417|title=Eugene Scalia is sworn in as Secretary of Labor (@USDOL)pic.twitter.com/aQbvTmBYGP|date=September 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAs of 2019, Scalia and his wife Patricia have seven children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/osec|title=Office of the Secretary &#124; U.S. Department of Labor|website=www.dol.gov}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Eugene Scalia}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081024104947/http://gibsondunn.com/lawyers/escalia Official law firm biography]\n* {{C-SPAN|eugenescalia}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alexander Acosta]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of Labor]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{USSecLabor}}\n{{Current U.S. Cabinet}}\n{{Trump cabinet}}\n{{US Presidential Line of Succession}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scalia, Eugene}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lawyers who have represented the United States government]]\n[[Category:Trump administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Labor officials]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of Labor]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n[[Category:Washington, D.C. Republicans]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n", "name_user": "2604:6000:1101:9b:2cab:a2a4:59ff:5eee", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugene_Scalia"}
{"title_page": "Bina Ramesh", "text_new": "{{Infobox Athlete\n |name                       = Bina Ramesh\n |event                = [[Javelin Throw]] \n |nationality               = {{FRA}} \n |birth_date         = {{birth-date and age |28 August 1979}}\n |birth_place         = [[Noum\u00e9a]]\n}}\n\n'''Bina Ramesh''' (born [[:fr:28 ao\u00fbt en sport|28 August]] [[1979 in sports|1979]] at [[Noum\u00e9a|Noumea]]) is a French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]] who specialises in the [[Javelin throw|Javelin]].\n\n==  Biography  ==\nShe won the bronze medal at the [[1996 World Junior Championships in Athletics|1996 World Junior Championships]] and also at the [[1997 European Athletics Junior Championships|1997 Junior European Championships]].\n\nShe won three French senior national Javelin championship titles in 1998, 2000 and 2004.\n\n===  Prize list  ===\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French Championships in Athletics]]   :  \n** 3-time winner of the javelin in [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1998|1998]],  [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 2000|2000]] and [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 2004|2004]].\n\n=== Records ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''personal records'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Place\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n|Javelin Throw (old model)\n|61.66 m\n|\n|1997\n|}\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n*  Docathl\u00e92003, French Athletics Federation, 2003 p428\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramesh, Bina}}\n[[Category:People from Noum\u00e9a]]\n[[Category:New Caledonian javelin throwers]]\n[[Category:French female javelin throwers]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Caledonian female athletes]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Athlete\n |name                       = Bina Ramesh\n |event                = [[Javelin Throw]] \n |nationality               = {{FRA}} \n |birth_date         = {{birth-date and age |28 August 1979}}\n |birth_place         = [[Noum\u00e9a]]\n}}\n\n'''Bina Ramesh''' (born [[:fr:28 ao\u00fbt en sport|28 August]] [[1979 in sports|1979]] at [[Noum\u00e9a|Noumea]]) is a French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]] who specialises in the [[Javelin throw|Javelin]].\n\n==  Biography  ==\nShe won the bronze medal at the [[1996 World Junior Championships in Athletics|1996 World Junior Championships]] and also at the [[1997 European Athletics Junior Championships|1997 Junior European Championships]].\n\nShe won three French senior national Javelin championship titles in 1998, 2000 and 2004.\n\n===  Prize list  ===\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French Championships in Athletics]]   :  \n** 3-time winner of the javelin in [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1998|1998]],  [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 2000|2000]] and [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 2004|2004]].\n\n=== Records ===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''personal records'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Place\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n|Javelin Throw (old model)\n|61.66 m\n|\n|1997\n|}\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n*  Docathl\u00e92003, French Athletics Federation, 2003 p428\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramesh, Bina}}\n[[Category:People from Noum\u00e9a]]\n[[Category:New Caledonian javelin throwers]]\n[[Category:French female javelin throwers]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Caledonian female athletes]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "tidy wikitable options", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bina_Ramesh"}
{"title_page": "Jo\u00eblle De Brouwer", "text_new": "{{Infobox Athlete\n |name                       = Jo\u00eblle De Brouwer\n |event                = [[middle distance running]]\n |years_active            = 1980s\n |nationality               = [[France|French]]\n |birth_date         = {{birth-date and age |18 October 1950}}\n |birth_place         = [[Maubeuge]]\n}}\n\n'''Jo\u00eblle De Brouwer''' (born October 18, 1950 at [[Maubeuge]]) is a former French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]] who specialized in [[Middle-distance running|middle distance]] running.\n\n==  Biography  ==\nShe won six French national Outdoor championships: 2 in the [[1500 metres|1 500 m]] and 4 in the [[3000 metres|3 000 m]].  She was also Indoor Champion of France in the 1,500&nbsp;m in 1981, and she won 8 French championships in [[Cross country running|cross-country]] from 1975 to 1984.\n\nShe improved nine times the [[List of French records in athletics|French record]] of the 3,000&nbsp;m, bringing it to 8:59.0.  On 1990. June 3, 1983, in Louvain, she establishes a new [[:fr:Record de France du 5 000 m\u00e8tres|French 5000m record]] of 15:52.60.\n\n=== Prize list  ===\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French Championships in Athletics]]   :  \n** 2 times winner of 1500 m [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1976|1976]] and [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1977|1977]]   \n** 4 times winner of 3000 m [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1975|1975]],  [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1978|1978]],  [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1980|1980]] and [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1981|1981]]   \n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme en salle|French Indoor Athletics  Championships]] :  \n** winner of 1500 m in 1981   \n* [[:fr:Championnats de France de cross-country|France Championships in Cross Country]]   :  \n** winner in 1975, 1976, 1977, 1978, 1979, 1981, 1983 and 1984\n\n=== Records ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''Personal Bests'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n|800 m\n|2:06.3\n|\n|1976\n|-\n|1 500 m\n|4:13.7\n|\n|1976\n|-\n|mile\n|4:39.1\n|[[Libourne]]\n|1985\n|-\n|3 000 m\n|8:58.94\n|\n|1980\n|-\n|5 000 m\n|15:52.60  \n|[[Leuven, Belgium|L\u00f6wen]]\n|June 1983\n|-\n|marathon\n|2:38:24\n|[[Neuf-Brisach]] \n|September 1983\n|}\n\n== Notes and references  ==\n* Docathl\u00e92003, F\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise d'athl\u00e9tisme, 2003, p.&nbsp;398\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:De Brouwer, Joelle}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:French female middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Athlete\n |name                       = Jo\u00eblle De Brouwer\n |event                = [[middle distance running]]\n |years_active            = 1980s\n |nationality               = [[France|French]]\n |birth_date         = {{birth-date and age |18 October 1950}}\n |birth_place         = [[Maubeuge]]\n}}\n\n'''Jo\u00eblle De Brouwer''' (born October 18, 1950 at [[Maubeuge]]) is a former French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]] who specialized in [[Middle-distance running|middle distance]] running.\n\n==  Biography  ==\nShe won six French national Outdoor championships: 2 in the [[1500 metres|1 500 m]] and 4 in the [[3000 metres|3 000 m]].  She was also Indoor Champion of France in the 1,500&nbsp;m in 1981, and she won 8 French championships in [[Cross country running|cross-country]] from 1975 to 1984.\n\nShe improved nine times the [[List of French records in athletics|French record]] of the 3,000&nbsp;m, bringing it to 8:59.0.  On 1990. June 3, 1983, in Louvain, she establishes a new [[:fr:Record de France du 5 000 m\u00e8tres|French 5000m record]] of 15:52.60.\n\n=== Prize list  ===\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French Championships in Athletics]]   :  \n** 2 times winner of 1500 m [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1976|1976]] and [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1977|1977]]   \n** 4 times winner of 3000 m [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1975|1975]],  [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1978|1978]],  [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1980|1980]] and [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1981|1981]]   \n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme en salle|French Indoor Athletics  Championships]] :  \n** winner of 1500 m in 1981   \n* [[:fr:Championnats de France de cross-country|France Championships in Cross Country]]   :  \n** winner in 1975, 1976, 1977, 1978, 1979, 1981, 1983 and 1984\n\n=== Records ===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''Personal Bests'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n|800 m\n|2:06.3\n|\n|1976\n|-\n|1 500 m\n|4:13.7\n|\n|1976\n|-\n|mile\n|4:39.1\n|[[Libourne]]\n|1985\n|-\n|3 000 m\n|8:58.94\n|\n|1980\n|-\n|5 000 m\n|15:52.60  \n|[[Leuven, Belgium|L\u00f6wen]]\n|June 1983\n|-\n|marathon\n|2:38:24\n|[[Neuf-Brisach]] \n|September 1983\n|}\n\n== Notes and references  ==\n* Docathl\u00e92003, F\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise d'athl\u00e9tisme, 2003, p.&nbsp;398\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:De Brouwer, Joelle}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:French female middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "tidy wikitable options", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jo%C3%ABlle_De_Brouwer"}
{"title_page": "Nicole Goullieux", "text_new": "{{Infobox athlete\n| name          = Nicole Goullieux\n| event         = [[800m]], [[cross country running]]\n| years_active  = 1952-1963\n| nationality   = [[France|French]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth-date and age |15 July 1931}}\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], France\n| height        = 1.61 m\n| club          = Racing Club de France\n}}\n\n'''Nicole Goullieux''' (born 15 July 1931 in [[Paris]]) is a former French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]], who specialized in the [[800 metres|800 meters]] and in Cross Country.\n\n== Biography ==\nShe won six titles [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French National 800m Championships]] in 1952, 1953, 1957, 1958, 1959 and 1962. She also won five [[:fr:Championnats de France de cross-country|French Cross Country Championships]],  between the years of 1956 to 1963\n\nIn 1959, she won the gold medal in the 800&nbsp;m during the [[Athletics at the 1959 Summer Universiade|Summer Universiade]], at [[Turin]] in the time 2:11.1. She participated in the [[Athletics at the 1960 Summer Olympics|1960 Olympics]] at Rome, but did not advance past the first round of the 800&nbsp;m trials.\n\nNicole Goullieux three times improved the [[:fr:Record de France du 800 m\u00e8tres|French 800 meters record]] running 2:12.7 and 2:10.5 in 1955 and 2:09.5 in 1959.\n\n=== Prize list ===\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French Championships in Athletics]]   :\n** winner of the 800m [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1952|1952]], [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1953|1953]], [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1957|1957]], [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1958|1958]], [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1959|1959]] and [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1962|1962]].\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France de cross-country|French Cross Country Championships]] :\n** winner in 1956, 1959, 1960, 1961 and 1963\n\n=== Records ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''Personal Bests'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n|800 m\n|2:09.5\n|\n|1959\n|}\n\n== Notes and references ==\n* {{Citation | title=Docathl\u00e9 2003 | pages=40, 117, 176, 406 | year=2003 | editor=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Fran\u00e7aise d'Athl\u00e9tisme |ISBN = 2-9512343-3-3}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{SR/Olympics|go/nicole-goullieux-1}}\n* {{Olympic Channel|nicole-goullieux}}\n* {{IOC profile|nicole-goullieux}}\n\n{{Footer Universiade Champions 800m Women}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goullieux, Nicole}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French female middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of France]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Universiade medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:Universiade gold medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox athlete\n| name          = Nicole Goullieux\n| event         = [[800m]], [[cross country running]]\n| years_active  = 1952-1963\n| nationality   = [[France|French]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth-date and age |15 July 1931}}\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], France\n| height        = 1.61 m\n| club          = Racing Club de France\n}}\n\n'''Nicole Goullieux''' (born 15 July 1931 in [[Paris]]) is a former French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]], who specialized in the [[800 metres|800 meters]] and in Cross Country.\n\n== Biography ==\nShe won six titles [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French National 800m Championships]] in 1952, 1953, 1957, 1958, 1959 and 1962. She also won five [[:fr:Championnats de France de cross-country|French Cross Country Championships]],  between the years of 1956 to 1963\n\nIn 1959, she won the gold medal in the 800&nbsp;m during the [[Athletics at the 1959 Summer Universiade|Summer Universiade]], at [[Turin]] in the time 2:11.1. She participated in the [[Athletics at the 1960 Summer Olympics|1960 Olympics]] at Rome, but did not advance past the first round of the 800&nbsp;m trials.\n\nNicole Goullieux three times improved the [[:fr:Record de France du 800 m\u00e8tres|French 800 meters record]] running 2:12.7 and 2:10.5 in 1955 and 2:09.5 in 1959.\n\n=== Prize list ===\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French Championships in Athletics]]   :\n** winner of the 800m [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1952|1952]], [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1953|1953]], [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1957|1957]], [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1958|1958]], [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1959|1959]] and [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1962|1962]].\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France de cross-country|French Cross Country Championships]] :\n** winner in 1956, 1959, 1960, 1961 and 1963\n\n=== Records ===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''Personal Bests'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n|800 m\n|2:09.5\n|\n|1959\n|}\n\n== Notes and references ==\n* {{Citation | title=Docathl\u00e9 2003 | pages=40, 117, 176, 406 | year=2003 | editor=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Fran\u00e7aise d'Athl\u00e9tisme |ISBN = 2-9512343-3-3}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{SR/Olympics|go/nicole-goullieux-1}}\n* {{Olympic Channel|nicole-goullieux}}\n* {{IOC profile|nicole-goullieux}}\n\n{{Footer Universiade Champions 800m Women}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goullieux, Nicole}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French female middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of France]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Universiade medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:Universiade gold medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "tidy wikitable options", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicole_Goullieux"}
{"title_page": "Gabrielle Meyer", "text_new": "{{short description|French sprinter}}\n{{Infobox athlete\n | name          = Gabrielle Meyer\n | event         = [[100 m]], [[200 m]]\n | nationality   = {{FRA}}\n | birth_date    = 10 May 1947\n | birth_place   = [[Toulouse]], Haute-Garonne, France\n | death_date    = {{death date and age|2018|11|18|1947|5|10|df=yes}}<ref name=\"FrenchATH\">[https://bases.athle.fr/asp.net/athletes.aspx?base=biographies&seq=475251484950465346535049 Profile of Gabrielle Meyer] {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n | club          = Toulouse UC\n}}\n\n'''Gabrielle Meyer''' (married name is '''Mor\u00e8re''') (10 May 1947 &ndash; 18 November 2018) was a French [[athlete]], who specialised in [[Sprint (running)|sprinting]].\n\n== Biography ==\nMeyer won five [[Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|champion of France]] ([[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|fr]]) titles, three in the [[100 metres]] in 1965, 1966 and 1967, and two in the [[200 metres]] in 1965 and 1966. In 1967, she won the gold medal in the 200m and the silver medal in the 100m during the [[Athletics at the 1967 Summer Universiade|Summer Universiade]] at Tokyo. In October 1967, in Mexico City, she equaled [[Record de France du 200 m\u00e8tres|France's 200m record]] ([[:fr:Record de France du 200 m\u00e8tres|fr]]) from [[Catherine Capdevielle]] in 23.7s. She participated in the [[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Olympics]] in Mexico City. Eliminated in the quarterfinals of the 100m, she took eighth in the [[4 \u00d7 100 metres relay|4 \u00d7 100 m]] relay. She was selected 18 times for France.\n\n=== Prize list ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%; margin-bottom: 10px;\"\n|+ International Awards\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Competition\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" | Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1967\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Athletics at the 1967 Summer Universiade|Summer Universiade]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Tokyo]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2nd\n|100 m\n|11.7s\n|-\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n| 200 m\n| 23.8s\n|-\n| 1968\n| [[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n| [[Mexico City|Mexico]]\n| align=\"center\" | 8th\n| 4 \u00d7 100 m Relay\n| 44 s 2\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1969\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[1969 European Athletics Championships|European Championships]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Athens]]\n| align=\"center\" | 5th\n| 200 m\n| 23.7s\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 4th\n| 4 \u00d7 100 m Relay\n| 44.6s\n|}\n\n=== National ===\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French Championships in Athletics]]:\n** Winner of the 100m 1965, 1966 and 1967\n** Winner of 200m 1965 and 1966\n\n== Records ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ Personal records\n\n! scope=\"col\" | Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n| 100 m\n| 11.55s\n|\n| 1967\n|-\n| 200 m\n| 23.66s\n|\n| 1967\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* {{Cite | author = Siukonen, Markku | author2 = Ahola, Matti | last-author-amp = yes | title = Suuri EM-kirja | pages=87, 95, 96, 112 | year=1990 | publisher=Sporttikustannus Oy | ISBN =951-8920-11-7}}\n* {{Cite | title=Docathl\u00e9 2003 | pages=39, 45, 118, 177, 421 | year=2003 | publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Fran\u00e7aise d'Athl\u00e9tisme | ISBN = 2-9512343-3-3 | language=fr}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/me/gabrielle-meyer-1.html |title=Gabrielle Meyer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082718/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/me/gabrielle-meyer-1.html |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=live}}\n* Dictionary of athletics by Robert Pariente: Extract in the No. 31 Wednesday, August 18, 1971 L'Equipe Magazine Athletics, with black and white photo of the applicant\n{{Footer Universiade Champions 200m Women}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meyer, Gabrielle}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:French female sprinters]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of France]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1968 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Universiade medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:Universiade gold medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Universiade silver medalists for France]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French sprinter}}\n{{Infobox athlete\n | name          = Gabrielle Meyer\n | event         = [[100 m]], [[200 m]]\n | nationality   = {{FRA}}\n | birth_date    = 10 May 1947\n | birth_place   = [[Toulouse]], Haute-Garonne, France\n | death_date    = {{death date and age|2018|11|18|1947|5|10|df=yes}}<ref name=\"FrenchATH\">[https://bases.athle.fr/asp.net/athletes.aspx?base=biographies&seq=475251484950465346535049 Profile of Gabrielle Meyer] {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n | club          = Toulouse UC\n}}\n\n'''Gabrielle Meyer''' (married name is '''Mor\u00e8re''') (10 May 1947 &ndash; 18 November 2018) was a French [[athlete]], who specialised in [[Sprint (running)|sprinting]].\n\n== Biography ==\nMeyer won five [[Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|champion of France]] ([[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|fr]]) titles, three in the [[100 metres]] in 1965, 1966 and 1967, and two in the [[200 metres]] in 1965 and 1966. In 1967, she won the gold medal in the 200m and the silver medal in the 100m during the [[Athletics at the 1967 Summer Universiade|Summer Universiade]] at Tokyo. In October 1967, in Mexico City, she equaled [[Record de France du 200 m\u00e8tres|France's 200m record]] ([[:fr:Record de France du 200 m\u00e8tres|fr]]) from [[Catherine Capdevielle]] in 23.7s. She participated in the [[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Olympics]] in Mexico City. Eliminated in the quarterfinals of the 100m, she took eighth in the [[4 \u00d7 100 metres relay|4 \u00d7 100 m]] relay. She was selected 18 times for France.\n\n=== Prize list ===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%; margin-bottom: 10px;\"\n|+ International Awards\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Competition\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" | Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1967\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Athletics at the 1967 Summer Universiade|Summer Universiade]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Tokyo]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2nd\n|100 m\n|11.7s\n|-\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n| 200 m\n| 23.8s\n|-\n| 1968\n| [[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n| [[Mexico City|Mexico]]\n| align=\"center\" | 8th\n| 4 \u00d7 100 m Relay\n| 44 s 2\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1969\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[1969 European Athletics Championships|European Championships]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Athens]]\n| align=\"center\" | 5th\n| 200 m\n| 23.7s\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 4th\n| 4 \u00d7 100 m Relay\n| 44.6s\n|}\n\n=== National ===\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French Championships in Athletics]]:\n** Winner of the 100m 1965, 1966 and 1967\n** Winner of 200m 1965 and 1966\n\n== Records ==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ Personal records\n\n! scope=\"col\" | Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n| 100 m\n| 11.55s\n|\n| 1967\n|-\n| 200 m\n| 23.66s\n|\n| 1967\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* {{Cite | author = Siukonen, Markku | author2 = Ahola, Matti | last-author-amp = yes | title = Suuri EM-kirja | pages=87, 95, 96, 112 | year=1990 | publisher=Sporttikustannus Oy | ISBN =951-8920-11-7}}\n* {{Cite | title=Docathl\u00e9 2003 | pages=39, 45, 118, 177, 421 | year=2003 | publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Fran\u00e7aise d'Athl\u00e9tisme | ISBN = 2-9512343-3-3 | language=fr}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/me/gabrielle-meyer-1.html |title=Gabrielle Meyer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082718/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/me/gabrielle-meyer-1.html |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=live}}\n* Dictionary of athletics by Robert Pariente: Extract in the No. 31 Wednesday, August 18, 1971 L'Equipe Magazine Athletics, with black and white photo of the applicant\n{{Footer Universiade Champions 200m Women}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meyer, Gabrielle}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:French female sprinters]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of France]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1968 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Universiade medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:Universiade gold medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Universiade silver medalists for France]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "tidy wikitable options", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabrielle_Meyer"}
{"title_page": "Annie Aliz\u00e9", "text_new": "{{short description|French sprinter}}\n{{Infobox Athlete\n |name                       = Annie Aliz\u00e9\n |event               = [[100 metres|100 m]], [[200 metres|200 m]]\n |nationality         = {{FRA}}\n |birth_date         = {{birth-date and age|14 July 1955}}\n |birth_place         = [[Mananjary, Fianarantsoa|Mananjary]], [[Madagascar]]\n}}\n\n'''Annie Aliz\u00e9,''' n\u00e9e Pellicia, (born 14 June 1955 at [[Mananjary, Fianarantsoa|Mananjary]] in [[Madagascar]]) is a former  French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]] in the [[Sprint (running)|sprints]].\n\n==  Biography  ==\nDuring the [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1977|France Championships of 1977 athletics]], she won both the 100 m  and  200 m sprint races. She also won two national titles indoors: the 50 m in 1978 and the 60m in 1979.\n\nIn 1979, she won the silver medal in the 200m at [[Athletics at the 1979 Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]] in Split. She ran for the Club C.A.M.N Villeurbanne.\n\n===  Prize list  ===\n* France Championships in Athletics   :  \n** winner of 100 m 1977.   \n** winner of 200 m 1977.   \n* Athletics Indoor Championships France   :  \n** winner of 50 m in 1978.   \n** winner of 60 m in 1979.\n\n=== Records ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''Personal records'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Race   \n! scope=\"col\" |  Performance   \n! scope=\"col\" | Place   \n! scope=\"col\" |  Date\n|-\n|100 m\n|11 s 39\n|\n|1978\n|-\n|200 m\n|23 s 37\n|\n|1979\n|}\n\n==  Notes and references  ==\n{{Reflist}}\n*  Docathl\u00e92003, French Athletics Federation, 2003, p.&nbsp;387\n\n==  External links  ==\n* [http://www.all-athletics.com/node/287629 All Athletics Profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Footer Mediterranean Champions 4x100m Women}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alize, Annie}}\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games gold medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games silver medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1975 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1979 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in athletics]]\n[[Category:French female sprinters]]\n[[Category:People from Vatovavy-Fitovinany]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French sprinter}}\n{{Infobox Athlete\n |name                       = Annie Aliz\u00e9\n |event               = [[100 metres|100 m]], [[200 metres|200 m]]\n |nationality         = {{FRA}}\n |birth_date         = {{birth-date and age|14 July 1955}}\n |birth_place         = [[Mananjary, Fianarantsoa|Mananjary]], [[Madagascar]]\n}}\n\n'''Annie Aliz\u00e9,''' n\u00e9e Pellicia, (born 14 June 1955 at [[Mananjary, Fianarantsoa|Mananjary]] in [[Madagascar]]) is a former  French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]] in the [[Sprint (running)|sprints]].\n\n==  Biography  ==\nDuring the [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1977|France Championships of 1977 athletics]], she won both the 100 m  and  200 m sprint races. She also won two national titles indoors: the 50 m in 1978 and the 60m in 1979.\n\nIn 1979, she won the silver medal in the 200m at [[Athletics at the 1979 Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]] in Split. She ran for the Club C.A.M.N Villeurbanne.\n\n===  Prize list  ===\n* France Championships in Athletics   :  \n** winner of 100 m 1977.   \n** winner of 200 m 1977.   \n* Athletics Indoor Championships France   :  \n** winner of 50 m in 1978.   \n** winner of 60 m in 1979.\n\n=== Records ===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''Personal records'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Race   \n! scope=\"col\" |  Performance   \n! scope=\"col\" | Place   \n! scope=\"col\" |  Date\n|-\n|100 m\n|11 s 39\n|\n|1978\n|-\n|200 m\n|23 s 37\n|\n|1979\n|}\n\n==  Notes and references  ==\n{{Reflist}}\n*  Docathl\u00e92003, French Athletics Federation, 2003, p.&nbsp;387\n\n==  External links  ==\n* [http://www.all-athletics.com/node/287629 All Athletics Profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Footer Mediterranean Champions 4x100m Women}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alize, Annie}}\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games gold medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games silver medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1975 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1979 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in athletics]]\n[[Category:French female sprinters]]\n[[Category:People from Vatovavy-Fitovinany]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "tidy wikitable options", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annie_Aliz%C3%A9"}
{"title_page": "Nicole Pani", "text_new": "{{Infobox Athlete\n | name                        = Nicole Pani\n | event                 = [[100 m]], [[200 m]]\n | nationality                = {{FRA}} \n | birth_date          = {{birth-date and age |30 October 1948}}\n | birth_place          = [[Suresnes]]\n | regionals = [[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships|Indoor European Championships]]\n|show-medals=yes\n| medaltemplates=\n{{Medal|Country | {{FRA}} }}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver| [[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships]]|[[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships|4 X 180m Relay]] \n}}\n\n}}\n\n'''Nicole Pani''' (born '''Montandon''' on 30 October [[1948 in sports|1948]] at [[Suresnes]]) is a former French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]], who specialised in [[Sprint (running)|sprinting]].\n\n==  Biography  ==\nPani became notable in the 1966 junior track where she ran 11.8s in the 100 m. and 24.3s in the 200 m. She won second place at the European Championships in the category over 200m. She married the long jumper, [[Jack Pani]].\n\nShe participated in the [[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Olympics]], at [[Mexico City|Mexico]] and placed fifth in the 200m (23.0s).\n\nSelected 29 times for French athletic teams, she won the silver medal in the 100m during the [[Athletics at the 1971 Mediterranean Games|1971 Mediterranean Game]]<nowiki/>s.  In 1972 she was second in the 4 \u00d7 1 lap relay<ref>The lap is 180 m</ref> in the [[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships|European Indoor Championships]] at [[Grenoble]], in the company of [[Mich\u00e8le Beugnet]],  [[Claudine Meire]] and [[Christiane Marlet]].\n\nShe titled in the 200m during the 1968 French Athletics Championships, and established multiple French national records in the 200m,  the 4 \u00d7 100m and the 4 \u00d7 200 m.\n\n===  prize list  ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%; margin-bottom: 10px;\"\n|+'''International Awards'''\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Competition\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n|-\n|1968\n|[[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]   \n|Mexico\n| align=\"center\" | 5th\n|200 m\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1971\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Athletics at the 1971 Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Izmir]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2nd\n|100 m\n|-\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2nd\n|4 \u00d7 100 m\n|-\n|1972\n|[[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships|European Indoor Championships]]\n|[[Grenoble]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2nd\n| 4 \u00d7 1 lap Relay\n|}\n\n=== Records ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''personal records'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n|[[100 metres|100 m]]\n|11.82s\n|\n|1975\n|-\n|[[200 metres|200 m]]\n|23.02s\n|\n|1968\n|-\n|[[400 metres|400 m]]\n|56.3s\n|\n|1972\n|}\n\n==  notes and references  ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==  External links  ==\n* <span class=\"indicateur-langue\">(<abbr class=\"abbr\" title=\"Langue : anglais\">in</abbr>)</span><span> Olympic profile</span><nowiki>   </nowiki>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mo/nicole-montandon-1.html Nicole Pani]<span> sure </span>''sports-reference.com''\n\n== Sources ==\n* ''DocAthl\u00e9 2003'', French Athletics Federation, p.&nbsp;421   \n* (*) The Athletics Equipe Magazine No. 32 of 28 September 1971   Robert Pariente sheet.\n{{Footer Mediterranean Champions 4x100m Women}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pani, Nicole}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:French female sprinters]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of France]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1968 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games gold medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games silver medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1971 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1975 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in athletics]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Athlete\n | name                        = Nicole Pani\n | event                 = [[100 m]], [[200 m]]\n | nationality                = {{FRA}} \n | birth_date          = {{birth-date and age |30 October 1948}}\n | birth_place          = [[Suresnes]]\n | regionals = [[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships|Indoor European Championships]]\n|show-medals=yes\n| medaltemplates=\n{{Medal|Country | {{FRA}} }}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver| [[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships]]|[[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships|4 X 180m Relay]] \n}}\n\n}}\n\n'''Nicole Pani''' (born '''Montandon''' on 30 October [[1948 in sports|1948]] at [[Suresnes]]) is a former French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]], who specialised in [[Sprint (running)|sprinting]].\n\n==  Biography  ==\nPani became notable in the 1966 junior track where she ran 11.8s in the 100 m. and 24.3s in the 200 m. She won second place at the European Championships in the category over 200m. She married the long jumper, [[Jack Pani]].\n\nShe participated in the [[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Olympics]], at [[Mexico City|Mexico]] and placed fifth in the 200m (23.0s).\n\nSelected 29 times for French athletic teams, she won the silver medal in the 100m during the [[Athletics at the 1971 Mediterranean Games|1971 Mediterranean Game]]<nowiki/>s.  In 1972 she was second in the 4 \u00d7 1 lap relay<ref>The lap is 180 m</ref> in the [[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships|European Indoor Championships]] at [[Grenoble]], in the company of [[Mich\u00e8le Beugnet]],  [[Claudine Meire]] and [[Christiane Marlet]].\n\nShe titled in the 200m during the 1968 French Athletics Championships, and established multiple French national records in the 200m,  the 4 \u00d7 100m and the 4 \u00d7 200 m.\n\n===  prize list  ===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%; margin-bottom: 10px;\"\n|+'''International Awards'''\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Competition\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n|-\n|1968\n|[[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]   \n|Mexico\n| align=\"center\" | 5th\n|200 m\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1971\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Athletics at the 1971 Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Izmir]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2nd\n|100 m\n|-\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2nd\n|4 \u00d7 100 m\n|-\n|1972\n|[[1972 European Athletics Indoor Championships|European Indoor Championships]]\n|[[Grenoble]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2nd\n| 4 \u00d7 1 lap Relay\n|}\n\n=== Records ===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''personal records'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n|[[100 metres|100 m]]\n|11.82s\n|\n|1975\n|-\n|[[200 metres|200 m]]\n|23.02s\n|\n|1968\n|-\n|[[400 metres|400 m]]\n|56.3s\n|\n|1972\n|}\n\n==  notes and references  ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==  External links  ==\n* <span class=\"indicateur-langue\">(<abbr class=\"abbr\" title=\"Langue : anglais\">in</abbr>)</span><span> Olympic profile</span><nowiki>   </nowiki>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mo/nicole-montandon-1.html Nicole Pani]<span> sure </span>''sports-reference.com''\n\n== Sources ==\n* ''DocAthl\u00e9 2003'', French Athletics Federation, p.&nbsp;421   \n* (*) The Athletics Equipe Magazine No. 32 of 28 September 1971   Robert Parien