{"title_page": "Nathalie Simon (athlete)", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2016}}{{notability|Sports|date=February 2016}}}}\n\n{{Infobox Athlete\n |name                       = Nathalie Simon\n |event                = [[400 m]]\n |nationality               = {{FRA}} \n |birth_date         = {{birth-date and age |14 April 1962}}\n |birth_place         = [[Le Petit-Quevilly]], [[France]]\n |height                    = 1.71m\n |club                   = Racing Club de France \n}}\n\n'''Nathalie Simon''' (n\u00e9e '''Chevallier''') (born 14 April 1962) is a former French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]], who specialised in the [[400 metres]].\n\n==  Biography  ==\nChampion of France [[400 metres|400 meters]] in [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1986|1986]] she was seventh in the 4 \u00d7 400 m relay at the [[1987 World Championships in Athletics|1987 World Championships]], at [[Rome]].  She participated in the following year in the [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul Olympics]]. Eliminated in the 400m heats, she took seventh in the  4 \u00d7 400 m relay.\n\nIn 1987, she won the gold medal in the 400m at [[Athletics at the 1987 Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]] at [[Latakia]], Syria.\n\n===  prize list  ===\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French Championships in Athletics]]   :  \n** winner of the 400m 1986\n\n=== Records ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''personal records'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n|400 m\n|52.05s\n|\n|1987\n|}\n\n==  notes and references  ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==  External links  ==\n* <span class=\"indicateur-langue\">(<abbr class=\"abbr\" title=\"Langue : anglais\">en</abbr>)</span><span> Olympic profile</span><nowiki>   </nowiki>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/si/nathalie-simon-1.html Nathalie Simon (athletics)]<span> sure </span>''sports-reference.com''\n{{Footer Mediterranean Champions 400m Women}}\n{{Footer Mediterranean Champions 4x100m Women}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simon, Nathalie}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:People from Le Petit-Quevilly]]\n[[Category:French female sprinters]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of France]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games gold medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1987 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in athletics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Seine-Maritime]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2016}}{{notability|Sports|date=February 2016}}}}\n\n{{Infobox Athlete\n |name                       = Nathalie Simon\n |event                = [[400 m]]\n |nationality               = {{FRA}} \n |birth_date         = {{birth-date and age |14 April 1962}}\n |birth_place         = [[Le Petit-Quevilly]], [[France]]\n |height                    = 1.71m\n |club                   = Racing Club de France \n}}\n\n'''Nathalie Simon''' (n\u00e9e '''Chevallier''') (born 14 April 1962) is a former French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]], who specialised in the [[400 metres]].\n\n==  Biography  ==\nChampion of France [[400 metres|400 meters]] in [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 1986|1986]] she was seventh in the 4 \u00d7 400 m relay at the [[1987 World Championships in Athletics|1987 World Championships]], at [[Rome]].  She participated in the following year in the [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul Olympics]]. Eliminated in the 400m heats, she took seventh in the  4 \u00d7 400 m relay.\n\nIn 1987, she won the gold medal in the 400m at [[Athletics at the 1987 Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]] at [[Latakia]], Syria.\n\n===  prize list  ===\n* [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme|French Championships in Athletics]]   :  \n** winner of the 400m 1986\n\n=== Records ===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+'''personal records'''\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n|400 m\n|52.05s\n|\n|1987\n|}\n\n==  notes and references  ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==  External links  ==\n* <span class=\"indicateur-langue\">(<abbr class=\"abbr\" title=\"Langue : anglais\">en</abbr>)</span><span> Olympic profile</span><nowiki>   </nowiki>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/si/nathalie-simon-1.html Nathalie Simon (athletics)]<span> sure </span>''sports-reference.com''\n{{Footer Mediterranean Champions 400m Women}}\n{{Footer Mediterranean Champions 4x100m Women}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simon, Nathalie}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:People from Le Petit-Quevilly]]\n[[Category:French female sprinters]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of France]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games gold medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1987 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in athletics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Seine-Maritime]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "tidy wikitable options", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nathalie_Simon_(athlete)"}
{"title_page": "Speaker of the House of Representatives of Nigeria", "text_new": "The '''Speaker of the House of Representatives''' is the presiding officer of the [[Federal House of Representatives]] of [[Nigeria]]. [[Femi Gbajabiamila]], was elected [[ Speaker of House of Representatives of Nigeria]] on June 11th, 2019 till June 11th, 2023.\n\n==History==\nSir Frederic Metcalfe of [[Great Britain]] became Speaker of the House of Representatives of Nigeria in 1955. He was replaced by the first indigenous [[Speaker (politics)|speaker]], [[Jaja Wachuku]], in 1959. As Speaker of the House, Wachuku received Nigeria's Instrument of [[Independence]], also known as Freedom Charter, on October 1, 1960, from [[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy|Princess Alexandra of Kent]] (Alexandra was [[Elizabeth II]]'s representative at the Nigerian Independence ceremonies). Chaha Biam hails from Ukum Local Government Area of Benue State. He was elected to the House of Representative on the platform of NPN in the 1983 general elections and was elected as the Speaker of House of Representative in the short lived second tenure of Alhaji Shehu Shagari, October 1, 1983 \u2013 December 31, 1983.\n\n==Selection and succession to presidency==\nThe speaker is chosen in an [[indirect election]] conducted within the House of Representatives. The Speaker is third in line for succession to the [[President of Nigeria|Nigerian presidency]], after the [[Vice President of Nigeria|Vice President]] and [[President of the Nigerian Senate|President of the Senate]].\n\n==List of Speakers==\n<!--  Commented out because image was deleted: [[Image:Nigerian-House-of-Representatives1.JPG|200px|thumb|Seal of the House of Representatives]] -->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Name!! Term !! Party\n|-\n| Sir [[Frederic Metcalfe]] || 1955\u20131959 ||\n|-\n| [[Jaja Wachuku]] || 1959\u20131960 || [[National Council of Nigeria and the Cameroons|NCNC]]\n|-\n| [[Ibrahim Jalo Waziri]] || 1960\u20131966 || [[Northern People's Congress|NPC]]\n|-\n| [[Edwin Ume-Ezeoke]] || 1979\u20131983 || [[National Party of Nigeria|NPN]]\n|-  \n| [[Chaha Biam]]       || 1983      ||  [[National Party of Nigeria|NPN]] \n|-\n| [[Salisu Buhari]] || 1999\u20132000 || [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Ghali Umar Na'Abba]] || 2000\u20132003|| [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Aminu Bello Masari]] || 2003\u20132007 || [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Patricia Etteh]] || 2007 || [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Dimeji Bankole]] || 2007\u20132011 || [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Aminu Waziri Tambuwal]] || 2011\u20132015 || [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP/APC]]\n|-\n| [[Yakubu Dogara]] || 2015\u20132019 || [[All Progressives Congress|APC]]/[[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Femi Gbajabiamila]] || 2019 ||\n[[All Progressives Congress| APC ]] \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Nigeria}}\n*[http://www.nassnig.org/House/index.htm Official website of the House of Representatives]\n*[http://www.assemblyonline.info Assemblyonline, news agency on Nigeria's National Assembly]\n\n{{Speaker Nigerian House of Representatives}}\n\n[[Category:Legislative speakers|Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the House of Representatives (Nigeria)| Chaha Biam speaker 1983]]\n[[Category:Lists of Members of the House of Representatives (Nigeria)|Speakers]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-gov-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Speaker of the House of Representatives''' is the presiding officer of the [[Federal House of Representatives]] of [[Nigeria]]. [[Femi Gbajabiamila]], was elected [[ Speaker of House of Representatives of Nigeria]] on June 11th, 2019 till June 11th, 2023.\n\n==History==\nSir Frederic Metcalfe of [[Great Britain]] became Speaker of the House of Representatives of Nigeria in 1955. He was replaced by the first indigenous [[Speaker (politics)|speaker]], [[Jaja Wachuku]], in 1959. As Speaker of the House, Wachuku received Nigeria's Instrument of [[Independence]], also known as Freedom Charter, on October 1, 1960, from [[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy|Princess Alexandra of Kent]] (Alexandra was [[Elizabeth II]]'s representative at the Nigerian Independence ceremonies). Chaha Biam hails from Ukum Local Government Area of Benue State. He was elected to the House of Representative on the platform of NPN in the 1983 general elections and was elected as the Speaker of House of Representative in the short lived second tenure of Alhaji Shehu Shagari, October 1, 1983 \u2013 December 31, 1983.\n\n==Selection and succession to presidency==\nThe speaker is chosen in an [[indirect election]] conducted within the House of Representatives. The Speaker is third in line for succession to the [[President of Nigeria|Nigerian presidency]], after the [[Vice President of Nigeria|Vice President]] and [[President of the Nigerian Senate|President of the Senate]].\n\n==List of Speakers==\n<!--  Commented out because image was deleted: [[Image:Nigerian-House-of-Representatives1.JPG|200px|thumb|Seal of the House of Representatives]] -->\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"2\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! Name!! Term !! Party\n|-\n| Sir [[Frederic Metcalfe]] || 1955\u20131959 ||\n|-\n| [[Jaja Wachuku]] || 1959\u20131960 || [[National Council of Nigeria and the Cameroons|NCNC]]\n|-\n| [[Ibrahim Jalo Waziri]] || 1960\u20131966 || [[Northern People's Congress|NPC]]\n|-\n| [[Edwin Ume-Ezeoke]] || 1979\u20131983 || [[National Party of Nigeria|NPN]]\n|-  \n| [[Chaha Biam]]       || 1983      ||  [[National Party of Nigeria|NPN]] \n|-\n| [[Salisu Buhari]] || 1999\u20132000 || [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Ghali Umar Na'Abba]] || 2000\u20132003|| [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Aminu Bello Masari]] || 2003\u20132007 || [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Patricia Etteh]] || 2007 || [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Dimeji Bankole]] || 2007\u20132011 || [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Aminu Waziri Tambuwal]] || 2011\u20132015 || [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP/APC]]\n|-\n| [[Yakubu Dogara]] || 2015\u20132019 || [[All Progressives Congress|APC]]/[[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]]\n|-\n| [[Femi Gbajabiamila]] || 2019 ||\n[[All Progressives Congress| APC ]] \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Nigeria}}\n*[http://www.nassnig.org/House/index.htm Official website of the House of Representatives]\n*[http://www.assemblyonline.info Assemblyonline, news agency on Nigeria's National Assembly]\n\n{{Speaker Nigerian House of Representatives}}\n\n[[Category:Legislative speakers|Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the House of Representatives (Nigeria)| Chaha Biam speaker 1983]]\n[[Category:Lists of Members of the House of Representatives (Nigeria)|Speakers]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-gov-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "tidy wikitable options", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speaker_of_the_House_of_Representatives_of_Nigeria"}
{"title_page": "Elea-Mariama Diarra", "text_new": "[[File:Elea-Mariama Diarra 2018.jpg|thumb|160px|Diarra in 2018]]\n'''Elea-Mariama Diarra''' (born 8 March [[1990 in sports|1990]] in [[Lyon]]) is a French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]], specialising in the [[400 metres|400 meters]]. She runs for [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu|D\u00e9cines Meyzieu]] Athletics.\n\n== Career ==\nShe won the national title in the 400 meters at the [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 2011|2011 French Championships]] d'[[Albi|Bleach]] in time of 53.01 s beating [[Marie Gayot]] and [[Muriel Hurtis-Houairi|Muriel Hurtis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.sport365.fr/autres-sports/athletisme/infos/article_543752_ChF-F-Diarra-sacree-sur-400m.shtml|title = Diarra sacr\u00e9e sur 400 m|date = 30 July 2011|website = sport365.fr|language=French}}</ref> In late July in Ostrava, she took third place in the [[4 \u00d7 400 metres relay|4 \u00d7 400 Metres Relay]] of the [[2011 European Athletics U23 Championships|European Championship (Under 21s)]] alongside her teammates from the team of France.\n\n== Prize list ==\n\n=== International ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Comp\u00e9tition\n! scope=\"col\" |Location\n! scope=\"col\" |Place\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" |Time\n|-\n|2009\n|[[2009 European Athletics Junior Championships|Junior European Championships]]\n|[[Novi Sad]]\n | align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"cc9966\" | 3rd\n|4 \u00d7 400 m\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|[[2011 European Athletics U23 Championships|European Championship hopes]]\n|[[Ostrava]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"cc9966\" | 3rd\n|4 \u00d7 400 m\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|[[2012 European Athletics Championships|European Championships]]\n|[[Helsinki]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2nd\n|4 \u00d7 400 m\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|[[2014 European Team Championships|European Team Championships]]\n|[[Braunschweig|Brunswick]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"cc9966\" |3rd\n|4 \u00d7 400 m\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2015\n|[[2015 European Athletics Indoor Championships|European Indoor Championships]]\n|[[Prague]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|4 \u00d7 400 m\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[2015 IAAF World Relays|Global Relay]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]]\n| align=\"center\" | 4th\n|4 \u00d7 400 m\n|3 min 26 s 68\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 6th\n|Medley Relay\n|11 min 06 s 33\n|-\n|[[2015 European Team Championships|European Team Championships]]\n|[[Cheboksary]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2nd\n|4 \u00d7 400 m\n|3 min 28 s 84\n|-\n|2017\n|[[2017 World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]]\n|[[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|22nd (h)\n|400 m\n|[[2017 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Women's 400 metres|52.06]]\n|}\n\n=== National ===\n* France Championships in Athletics   : Winner of the 400 m in 2011\n\n== Records ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Performance\n! scope=\"col\" |Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n|-\n|400 m\n|52 s 42\n|<span class=\"flagicon\">[[File:Flag_of_France.svg|border|20x20px|Drapeau : France]]</span> [[Nancy, France|Nancy]]\n|1 July 2015\n|-\n|400m Indoor\n|54 s 02\n|<span class=\"flagicon\">[[File:Flag_of_France.svg|border|20x20px|Drapeau : France]]</span> [[Eaubonne]]\n|14 February 2015\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IAAF name|id = 251704|name = Elea Mariama Diarra|initiale = D}}\n*  Biography of [http://bases.athle.com/asp.net/athletes.aspx?base=biographies&seq=225026 Mariama Diarra Elea] on the site of the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise d'athl\u00e9tisme|FFA]]\n\n{{Footer European Indoor Champions 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay Women}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diarra, Elea-Mariama}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French female sprinters]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lyon]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2018 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games silver medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in athletics]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Elea-Mariama Diarra 2018.jpg|thumb|160px|Diarra in 2018]]\n'''Elea-Mariama Diarra''' (born 8 March [[1990 in sports|1990]] in [[Lyon]]) is a French [[Sport of athletics|athlete]], specialising in the [[400 metres|400 meters]]. She runs for [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu|D\u00e9cines Meyzieu]] Athletics.\n\n== Career ==\nShe won the national title in the 400 meters at the [[:fr:Championnats de France d'athl\u00e9tisme 2011|2011 French Championships]] d'[[Albi|Bleach]] in time of 53.01 s beating [[Marie Gayot]] and [[Muriel Hurtis-Houairi|Muriel Hurtis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.sport365.fr/autres-sports/athletisme/infos/article_543752_ChF-F-Diarra-sacree-sur-400m.shtml|title = Diarra sacr\u00e9e sur 400 m|date = 30 July 2011|website = sport365.fr|language=French}}</ref> In late July in Ostrava, she took third place in the [[4 \u00d7 400 metres relay|4 \u00d7 400 Metres Relay]] of the [[2011 European Athletics U23 Championships|European Championship (Under 21s)]] alongside her teammates from the team of France.\n\n== Prize list ==\n\n=== International ===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Comp\u00e9tition\n! scope=\"col\" |Location\n! scope=\"col\" |Place\n! scope=\"col\" |Event\n! scope=\"col\" |Time\n|-\n|2009\n|[[2009 European Athletics Junior Championships|Junior European Championships]]\n|[[Novi Sad]]\n | align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"cc9966\" | 3rd\n|4 \u00d7 400 m\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|[[2011 European Athletics U23 Championships|European Championship hopes]]\n|[[Ostrava]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"cc9966\" | 3rd\n|4 \u00d7 400 m\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|[[2012 European Athletics Championships|European C